Reallocation effects of the minimum wage

Quarterly Journal of Economics, Volume 137, Issue 1, February 2022: 267â328

by Christian Dustmann, Attila Lindner, Uta SchÃ¶nberg, Matthias Umkehrer, Philipp vom Berge

2022å¹´04æ12æ¥ 14:46

Summary

  • German minimum wage of 2015 increased wages but did not reduce employment.
  • Absence of disemployment is due to reallocation of workers from low-wage paying firms to high-wage paying firms.
  • This reduced the wage inequality at the lower tail of distribution.
  • Low-wage paying firms are small establishments with lower productivity.
  • Higher-wage paying firms are more efficient firms.
  • Therefore, on average, minimum wage introduction increased the worker welfare and allocative efficiency of workers.
  • Workers commute longer hours for higher wages, especially males.
  • Outcomes are consistent with monopolistic competition in labour markets.
  • First to show allocative/efficiency effects of minimum wages without structural estimation.

Intro

Context

Jan 2015: Uniform â¬8.50/hour with 15% of workers earning below it.
Unemployed in prev year, work shorter hours, hired at small establishments.
MW/Median wage = .48 (.36 US; .61 France).

  • Economists: Minimum wages will reduce employment by 900K.

Data

Sources

Panel of all job spells with employee information
Administrative records of Federal Employment Agencyâs Statistics Department

Panel of earnings and hours of jobs
Employee Histories of the Institute for Employment Research in Nuremberg

Imputations

Work hours available until 2014. Proxy with mean working hours in each working time status category (full time, part time, marginal) for 2015 onwards.

Even reported work hours until 2014 are a mix of actual and contractual hours. Multiply hours by 1.19 for establishments reporting actual hours, where the latter is decided by 90% of full time workers working less than 35 hours per week. Aggregate hours are similar with GSOEP data.

NAs in working time status are imputed with Government research agencyâs algorithm. NAs in education are imputed with another Gov research agencyâs algorithm.

Preparations

Annual panel of all job spells for 2011-2016. Only main job was chosen for individuals with more than 1 job.
Annual panel of all 401 districts for 2011-2016. Wage, hours, employment for each work time category, firm characteristics.
Annual panel of establishments. Appendix C uses this although not written explicitly.

Identification

Job spell panel

Bin wise growth (after): \(\Delta_{2} y_{it}=y_{it}-y_{it-2}\) \[\begin{equation} \Delta_{2} y_{it}=\sum_{k}\mathbb 1[b_{k-1}<w_{it-2}\leqslant b_{k}]\tilde{\gamma}_{kt}+\beta x_{it-2}+e_{it}. \tag{1} \end{equation}\] Bin wise growth deviations from 2011 vs.Â 2013 (before-after): Robust to constant macroeconomic changes or constant mean reversal. \(\delta_{kt}\) for higher wage bins are near zero, affirming this assumption. \[\begin{equation} \Delta_{2} y_{it}=\sum_{k}\mathbb 1[b_{k-1}<w_{it-2}\leqslant b_{k}](\gamma_{k2013}+\gamma_{kt}) +\beta x_{it-2}+e_{it}. \tag{2} \end{equation}\] DID estimates for low wage bin \(k\): Assumes a common trend between low \(k\) and high \(\kappa\) wage bins. \[ \gamma^{DID}_{kt}=\gamma_{kt}-\bar{\gamma}_{t}, \quad \bar{\gamma}_{t}=\sum_{\kappa>k}^{K}\frac{\gamma_{\kappa t}}{K-\kappa+1}. \]

  • \(\hat{\delta}_{\kappa t}\simeq 0\).
  • \(\hat{\delta}_{kt}>0\) for \(t=2015\) onwards.
  • Interacting bins with local unemploymen rates does not change results, so no indication of individual trends.

District panel

Dose-response (exposure-response) \[\begin{equation} \begin{aligned} Y_{rt}&=\alpha_{r}+\zeta_{t}+\sum_{\substack{\tau=2011\\ \tau\neq 2014}}^{2016}\gamma_{\tau}\overline{GAP}_{r}+\epsilon_{rt},\\ \overline{GAP}_{r}&= \sum_{t=2011}^{2014}GAP_{rt}. \end{aligned} \tag{4} \end{equation}\] with GAP measuring percent increase necessary to achieve minimum wage \(MW\) for all workers, or exposure to the \(MW\) shock. \[ GAP_{rt}=\frac{\Sigma_{i\in r}h_{i}\max \{0, MW-w_{it}\}}{\Sigma_{i\in r}h_{i}w_{it}}, \] This estimator is more flexible than regular DID. This assumes post period impacts to be constant due to time effects \(\zeta_{t}\). One can drop \(\zeta_{t}\) and let impacts to be time variant \(\delta_{post, t}\) on \(\overline{GAP}_{r}\times 1[\tau=t]\). No staggered introduction of the policy, so TWFE estimator is fine. DID with district-specific (all period) linear time trend \(\beta_{r}\) and time effects \(\zeta_{t}\): Assumes linear trend to be constant and allows to vary across districts. Homogenous impact (can be made to be conditional on initial conditions). \[\begin{equation} Y_{rt}=\alpha_{r}+\zeta_{t}+\delta_{post}\overline{GAP}_{r}\times Post_{t}+\beta_{r}t+\epsilon_{rt}. \tag{5} \end{equation}\]

Results

Impacts on wages and employment

Job spell panel

See the figures at the top.

District panel

Robustness and heterogenous impact checks

  • Job spell panel and district panel both give similar results.
  • Many checks, including Table VI. In Appendix C, establishment level estimation of outcome rate of change on exposure, similar to Harasztosi and Lindner (2019Harasztosi, PÃ©ter, and Attila Lindner. 2019. âWho Pays for the Minimum Wage?â American Economic Review 109 (8): 2693â2727.).
    Not sure how: ``The small negative employment effect at the establishment level does not contradict the evidence on the absence of disemployment effect at the regional and individual levelsââ (p.319).
  • Using establishment level analysis, estimated labour demand elasticity is relatively small, -.26 or -.31, which is in line with previous studies (Appendix pp.65-66).
    This is consistent with previous studies that NTG sectors are less affected by minimum wages by passing on the costs to consumers.
  • Nontradeable sectors show more pronounced reallocation of workers. Due possibly to the ability to set prices higher which can accommodate workers at higher wages.

Impacts on characteristics of hired establishment

Job spell panel

Abowd, Kramarz, and Margolis (1999Abowd, John M., Francis Kramarz, and David N. Margolis. 1999. âHigh Wage Workers and High Wage Firms.â Econometrica 67 (2): 251â333.) allows estimation of individual and firm fixed effects using mover data.

  • Basic idea: Use movers (that can eliminate worker FEs by first-differencing) to get differences of firm FEs. Set the reference firmâs FE to zero. Then impute worker FEs by subtracting estimated firm FEs from wages.
  • Efficiency of this method depends on the number of movers to each firms. There are many works that expand on AKM.

District panel

Nonpecuniary impacts

Table VIII shows increased driving distance by 3.3 km for men, .76 km for women (1.77 km overall).

  • Absorption of workers at higher paying establishments may have come at nonpecuniary costs of workers.

Despite this, authors say (p.323):

workers will on average be no worse off after the introduction of the minimum wage, provided that the minimum wage does not lower employment.

the exit of inefficient firms may leave some consumers worse off despite being able to purchase similar products at a lower price. For example, some consumers may prefer nearby restaurants and shops even if they charge higher prices than restaurants and shops further away, but some of these small businesses close down after the minimum wage is implemented.

Welfare impacts are heterogenous and one cannot give a definitive answer. But authors tend to write that it improved on average.

A model explaining results

Worker \(i\) at firm \(j\) \[ u_{ij}=\beta \ln w_{j}+\epsilon_{ij}. \] Worker \(i\) in unemployment status \[ u_{ib}=b+\epsilon_{ib}. \] Assuming type I extreme value distributed errors gives for the set of firms in competition \(J^{M}\) and population of \(N\) workers: \[ P\left[{\mbox{argmax}\atop{\scriptsize k\in J^{M}}}\{u_{ij}, u_{ib}\}=j\right]= \frac{e^{\beta \ln w_{j}}}{e^{b}+\sum_{k\in J^{M}}\beta \ln w_{k}}=N\lambda^{M}e^{\beta \ln w_{j}}. \] Taking logs \[\begin{equation} \ln l_{j}=\ln N+\ln \lambda^{M}+\beta \ln w_{j}. \tag{D.1} \label{D1} \end{equation}\] The labour supply curve in \(\eqref{D1}\) is upward sloping. Similarly for unemployment probability \[ \mbox{unemployment rate}=N\lambda^{M}e^{b}. \] Firmâs problem with productivity parameter \(\phi_{j}\) and a fixed cost of hiring \(F\): \[ \max_{l_{j}} \;\;\; p_{j}\frac{1}{\phi_{j}}\ln l_{j}-w_{j}l_{j}-F \] FOC gives \[ \frac{p_{j}}{\phi_{j}}\frac{1}{l_{j}}=w_{j}\left(\frac{1+\beta}{\beta}\right), \quad \beta=\frac{dl_{j}}{dw_{j}}\frac{w_{j}}{l_{j}}. \] Taking logs \[\begin{equation} \ln l_{j}=-\ln \phi_{j}+\ln\left(\frac{1+\beta}{\beta}\right)-\ln \left(\frac{w_{j}}{p_{j}}\right). \tag{D.3} \label{D3} \end{equation}\] Labour market equilibium gives \[\begin{equation} \ln l_{j}=\frac{1}{1+\beta}\left[\beta\ln\left(\frac{p_{j}}{\phi_{j}}\frac{\beta}{1+\beta}\right) +\ln N+\ln \lambda^{M}\right]. \tag{D.4} \label{D4} \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} \ln w^{M}_{j}=\frac{1}{1+\beta}\left[\ln\left(\frac{p_{j}}{\phi_{j}}\frac{\beta}{1+\beta}\right) -\ln N-\ln \lambda^{M}\right]. \tag{D.5} \label{D5} \end{equation}\]

Predictions

  1. \(\phi_{j}\) \(\downarrow\) \(\sim\) \(l_{j}\) \(\uparrow\)
  2. \(\phi_{j}\) \(\downarrow\) \(\sim\) \(w^{M}_{j}\) \(\uparrow\)
  3. \(\phi_{j}\) \(\downarrow\) \(\sim\) \(\pi_{j}\) \(\uparrow\)
  4. Binding minimum wage on non-exiting firms \(\Rightarrow\) \(l_{j}\) \(\uparrow\).
  5. Non-binding minimum wage on non-exiting firms \(\Rightarrow\) \(l_{j}\) \(\uparrow\) or \(\downarrow\)

Point 4 can be seen by noting that firmâs problem under MW, conditional on non-exit, is that they act as a price taker because the wage is fixed: \[ \max_{l_{j}} \;\;\; p^{MW}_{j}\frac{1}{\phi_{j}}\ln l_{j}-w^{MW}_{j}l_{j}-F \] with: \[ \ln l^{MW}_{j} = -\ln \phi_{j}-\ln \left(\frac{w^{MW}_{j}}{p^{MW}_{j}}\right). \]

  • Digression on de facto price taker assumption. If the compulsory rise of wages to \(w^{MW}\) lowers labour costs through reduced hiring/firing costs and on efficiency wage ground, the marginal costs of labour may become flat for a range of \(l_{j}\) immediately after the rise. This gives rise to a window of \(l_{j}\) that makes the firm to be a de facto price taker.
  • This holds if the parameters are right that \(w^{MW}\) is not too low so the marginal labour costs do not start to increase nor too high so the firms can stay in the market.

We assume firms pay a higher product wage under the minimum wage, or \(\frac{w^{MW}_{j}}{p^{MW}_{j}}>\frac{w_{j}}{p_{j}}\). \[ \begin{aligned} \ln l^{MW}_{j}-\ln l_{j} &= \left\{-\ln \phi_{j}-\ln \left(\frac{w^{MW}_{j}}{p^{MW}_{j}}\right)\right\} -\left\{-\ln \phi_{j}-\ln\left(\frac{1+\beta}{\beta}\right)-\ln \left(\frac{w_{j}}{p_{j}}\right)\right\},\\ &= \ln\left(\frac{1+\beta}{\beta}\right)+\ln \left(\frac{w_{j}}{p_{j}}\right)-\ln \left(\frac{w^{MW}_{j}}{p_{j}}\right),\\ &>0 \quad \mbox{if minimum wage is not too high or }\beta\mbox{ is small (near horizontal supply curve)}. \end{aligned} \]

For non-binding firms, increased wages from minimum wages in the market can increase the wages that causes reduction in production, or, the exit of firms may reduce wages that increases production. So it can go either way.
